{"action": "edit", "code": "def traverse_pixels(input_grid: np.ndarray, ngrid: np.ndarray, mindex: int) -> None:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function traverses all pixels whose row number is less than mindex in input_grid.\n    For each pixel, it calls check_and_update_pixel to update the corresponding pixel in ngrid.\n    \"\"\"\n    for i in range(mindex):\n        for j in range(input_grid.shape[1]):\n            check_and_update_pixel(input_grid, ngrid, i, j, mindex)\ndef find_yellow_line_index(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> int:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes in a n*n grid with multiple color pixels and returns the index of the yellow line.\n    \"\"\"\n    for i in range(input_grid.shape[0]):\n        if np.array_equal(input_grid[i], np.array([yellow] * input_grid.shape[1])):\n            return i\n    return -1\ndef main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    In the input, you should see a n*n grid with multiple color pixels.\n    \"\"\"\n    mindex = find_yellow_line_index(input_grid)\n    ngrid = np.zeros((input_grid.shape[0] // 2, input_grid.shape[1]))\n    ans_grid = new_function_name(input_grid, mindex, ngrid)\n    return ans_grid\ndef check_and_update_pixel(input_grid: np.ndarray, ngrid: np.ndarray, x: int, y: int, mindex: int) -> None:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function checks if the pixel at (x, y) in input_grid is the same as the pixel at (x+mindex+1, y).\n    If they are the same, it sets the corresponding pixel in ngrid to 0, otherwise it sets it to green.\n    \"\"\"\n    if input_grid[x][y] == input_grid[x + mindex + 1][y]:\n        ngrid[x][y] = 0\n    else:\n        ngrid[x][y] = green\ndef new_function_name(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes in a n*n grid with multiple color pixels and returns a new grid ngrid.\n    Traverse all pixels whose row number is less than mindex in inputgrid, set the pixel coordinates as (x, y),\n    if the value of the pixel is the same as the value of (x+mindex+1, y